Each measurement was carried out in five parallel times and ultimately averaged. As is known to all, the sensor response can be defined as S = Ra/Rg (for reducing gases) or S = Rg/Ra (for oxidizing gases), where the Ra and Rg are the recorded stable resistance of the sensor in ambient air and target gases, respectively. It is worth noting that response time (τ
                           res
                        ) and recovery time (τ
                           rec
                        ) are defined as the time to reach a steady state of 90 % after filling with target gas or ambient air.

The relative humidity (RH) also plays a vital role in the practical application environment, thus, a series of relative humidity levels (35–80% RH, 25 ± 2 °C) is simulated by adding the DIW onto the hot evaporation block in the measurement chamber. Then, the relative humidity dependence of 100-ppm gas is measured and illustrated in Fig. 8e. It is observed that response gradually decreases as the humidity increases to 80% RH. IO-2@CQDs shows the approximate response of 22.39 when RH reaches 80%, which can be assigned to the competing adsorption of the water molecules and formaldehyde gas. How to further improve the anti-humidity performance will be one of the challenges in our subsequent efforts. For a more visual comparison of HCHO-sensing properties, a five-axis radar diagram with respect to optimal operating temperature coefficient (1/OOT), response (S), Sensing-kinetic coefficient (1/τres
                         and 1/τrec
                        ), and selectivity coefficient (Q) is plotted, just as shown in Fig. 8f. Notably, the IO-2@CQDs with marked green color occupies the largest area, demonstrating the more balanced HCHO-sensing properties [44].
